Definition
Masked Self‑Attention – a variant of self‑attention where each position can only attend to itself and preceding positions, enforced by a masking matrix.

🎯 Masked Multi‑Head Attention





Referred to as “mask‑self‑attention” in the lecture.



It is a different flavor of multi‑head attention that incorporates a mask to enforce the auto‑regressive property during decoding.



Without the mask, the decoder could cheat by looking at future tokens, breaking the sequential generation requirement.



Definition
Mask – a binary matrix applied to the attention scores that sets the scores of illegal (future) positions to (-\infty) before the softmax, forcing their attention weights to zero.

How it works





Query, Key, Value matrices are computed from the current decoder hidden states.



The mask is added to the attention score matrix.



Softmax yields attention weights that only consider current and previous tokens.



The weighted sum produces the masked attention output, which is then processed by the usual add‑&‑norm and feed‑forward sub‑layers.

📈 Auto‑Regressive vs. Non‑Auto‑Regressive Behavior







Phase



Model Behavior



Reason





Inference (prediction)



Auto‑regressive – each generated token conditions on all previously generated tokens.



Guarantees sequential dependence required for language generation.





Training



Non‑auto‑regressive (teacher forcing) – the decoder receives the ground‑truth previous token rather than its own prediction.



Speeds up training and provides stable gradients.



Definition
Auto‑Regressive Model – a model that generates a sequence by repeatedly conditioning on the tokens it has already produced.



Definition
Teacher Forcing – during training, the correct previous token (from the dataset) is fed into the decoder instead of the model’s own previous prediction.

Why the discrepancy?





Training speed: Using the true previous token avoids the need to wait for the model’s own output at each step.



Learning signal: Provides the correct context, allowing the loss to be computed directly against the target token.

🧩 Cross‑Attention (Encoder‑Decoder Attention)





After masked self‑attention, the decoder attends to the encoder’s output via cross‑attention.



This layer allows the decoder to incorporate information from the source sequence (e.g., English sentence when translating to Hindi).

🏃‍♂️ Computational Considerations





Sequential nature of decoding makes training slower if we kept the auto‑regressive loop during training.



With teacher forcing, each training example still processes the decoder’s full stack once per token, but the mask prevents future‑token leakage.



For long sequences (e.g., 300‑token paragraphs), the decoder’s sub‑layers are executed 300 times per example, which can be a performance bottleneck.

📚 Recap of Encoder Building Blocks (reused in Decoder)

Self‑Attention – captures intra‑sentence relationships.

Positional Encoding – adds order information to token embeddings.

Add‑&‑Norm – residual connection followed by layer normalization.

Feed‑Forward Network – two linear layers with a ReLU activation in between.

These components are identical in both encoder and decoder, simplifying the overall architecture.

🔍 Key Takeaways

The decoder’s masked multi‑head attention is essential for preserving the auto‑regressive property during generation.



Training employs teacher forcing (non‑auto‑regressive) to improve efficiency, while inference relies on true auto‑regressive behavior.



